    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing wine with chicken dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is automatically choosing white wine without considering the preparation method. Many people miss that dishes like coq au vin, BBQ chicken, or chicken with mushroom sauce actually pair better with red wines. Always consider the cooking method, seasonings, and sauces rather than just the protein when making your selection.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which wines offer the best value for chicken dinner pairings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Portuguese Vinho Verde ($8-12) offers excellent value for lighter chicken dishes with its crisp acidity and slight effervescence. For richer preparations, Spanish Tempranillo ($10-15) and French Côtes du Rhône ($12-18) provide great quality at reasonable prices. These wines are food-friendly, widely available, and complement chicken's versatility without breaking the budget.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I use the same wine for cooking and drinking with chicken?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, using the same wine for cooking and drinking creates harmonious flavor integration throughout your meal. A dry white wine like Sauvignon Blanc or Pinot Grigio works excellently for both deglazing the pan and serving alongside the finished dish. However, avoid cooking with expensive wines since heat diminishes their complexity—save premium bottles for drinking.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good non-wine alternatives that pair well with chicken?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Craft beer, particularly wheat beers and pilsners, complement fried and grilled chicken beautifully with their crisp, clean finish. Sparkling cider offers similar acidity to white wine and works wonderfully with herb-roasted chicken. For non-alcoholic options, sparkling grape juice or kombucha with fruity notes can provide the acidic contrast that makes wine pairings so successful.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How far in advance should I open wine for chicken dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most white wines paired with chicken should be opened just before serving to preserve their fresh, crisp character. Light reds like Pinot Noir benefit from 15-30 minutes of breathing to soften tannins and enhance aromatics. Only full-bodied reds used with heavily spiced or sauced chicken dishes need longer decanting—typically 30-60 minutes before your meal.</p>
